A total of 200 clinical respiratory sample extracts were tested to determine clinical sensitivity and specificity of the real-time assays (Table 3
). KIV DNA was detected in 13 samples by the KIV conventional PCR and both KIV rtPCR assays. Two specimens were positive by the KIV conventional and KI-A real-time methods, but were negative by the KI-B assay (Samples 1 and 2; Table 4
). These were considered false-negative results by the KI-B assay. Five samples gave positive results in both KIV rtPCR assays and were negative by conventional PCR, and a further five samples were positive by KI-A alone. All of these samples provided high cycle threshold (Ct) values in the rtPCR methods (Samples 3–11, 21; Table 4).
